timeline.bodyText: Can this be done in the service? It's not really the job of a Controller to do this kind of logic. Generally Controller classes should have very little logic in MVC, they serve mainly to provide a translation from API semantics to business layer semantics.
timeline.author: nikklassen

replies.bodyText: Agree with you. Moved this logic to service layer.
replies.author: dhanyak-btc

timeline.author: nikklassen
nikklassen

replies.bodyText: We are following this approach consistently in audit-log-service, participant-manager-service and oauth-scim-service. We'll be using ErrorCode instead of creating multiple *NotFound exception classes.
replies.author: dhanyak-btc

replies.bodyText: Why are you adopting this pattern though? It's contrary to what we talked about with using Exceptions. You are basically going back to the old way of writing code where null means that an error occured.
replies.author: nikklassen

timeline.author: nikklassen

replies.bodyText: We are following this approach consistently in audit-log-service, participant-manager-service and oauth-scim-service. We'll be using ErrorCode instead of creating multiple *NotFound exception classes.
replies.author: dhanyak-btc

replies.bodyText: This impacts control flow though. By using not found exceptions we can jump right to the exception handling code and build the response there. You're free to create a base NotFound exception and handle that one instead.
replies.author: nikklassen

replies.bodyText: Mistake 4: Use exceptions to control the flow   Since you've already created ErrorCodeException, we'll go with that approach. We are planning to fix ErrorCode related issues together and submit a new PR.
replies.author: dhanyak-btc

replies.bodyText: That blog post is referring to using exceptions to control the flow within a single method, as it says "better use proper conditions to break your loops or if-else-statements". Going to global exception handling code for a request is not at all the same thing.
replies.author: nikklassen

replies.bodyText: That's the opposite of what we want to do. Every test should be able to be run by itself, and in any order
